The name of this Exceptional Suite is a
reminder that the history of La Mamounia
dates back to the 18th century, when
Prince Al Mamoun received a sumptuous
thirteen-hectare orchard from his father
as a wedding gift.
It is to the splendour of that era that the
décor pays homage, an expression of
supreme luxury with its carved wooden
ceilings, chiselled plaster friezes and
zellige mosaics.

Intimate and refined
L’Asiatique par Jean-Georges restaurant is one of
finest creations to have emerged from La Mamounia’s
latest renovation.
It is a place of many influences, both in terms of its
stunning setting and its menu, which will take you on
a journey through a multitude of Far Eastern flavours.
From the original restaurant, the Patrick Jouin - Sanjit
Manku duo have chosen to retain the superb traditional
surroundings, revamping them with furnishings that
play on the restaurant’s graceful lines and contrasting
pale wood with deep indigo blue fabrics.
The light fittings create a warm and intimate
atmosphere.
And both inside and out, the establishment is as
exotic as a map of the world, reimagined by talented
explorers of design and décor.

A true Moroccan lounge
Perched on the top floor of the Le Marocain restaurant,
Le Club is one of La Mamounia’s best kept secrets.
Escape here to admire the setting sun over a pre- or postdinner cocktail, linger under the tent before heading out onto
the bar terrace with its beautiful views over the hotel Gardens,
and soak up an enchanting mixture of music and calm...
Here, cocktails and tapas dishes make up a menu with a
distinctly Moroccan feel.
The cocktail menu invites you to sample a selection
of argan oil, orange blossom, honey, amlou (a Berber
preparation made from honey and almonds) and dates in
its “Creations from the Garden” mix.
While the tapas menu features delights such as carrot
hummus roasted in cumin-flavoured olive oil and
served with batbout bread, crispy aubergine enhanced
with roasted almonds and honey, and sardine roulades
seasoned with coriander, to name but a few.

__data__.text:
A gourmet break in the heart
of La Mamounia
A magical place born of the hotel’s 2020 metamorphosis,
Le Salon de Thé par Pierre Hermé is one of the many
delightful features of La Mamounia.
Calm and welcoming, it occupies an intimate space,
complete with inviting sofas and armchairs, which
opens out into the radiant light of its Andalusian patio.
The atmosphere here is that of a winter garden, with
the gentle babbling of the marble fountain that seems
to rise up from the ground to greet the tea room’s
monumental, crystal chandelier.
This enchanting setting plays on contrasts of sleek
modernity, with the beautiful deep blue seats by Patrick
Jouin, juxtaposed against the delicate ornamental
motifs of the traditional Moroccan floor lamps.

Surface area  114 sqm
Up to 4 people

Garden and Pool View


Overlooking the flower-filled Gardens, swimming
pool and Atlas Mountains, the Majorelle Suite
spans 114 m² and comprises two bedrooms. The
first features a double bed; the second two singles
facing a rotunda-style window whose views
beckon you to gaze out over the hotel Gardens.
The suite also boasts two bathrooms with separate
shower and bathtub.
In homage to the artist, Majorelle blue
punctuates the décor of the suite, enlivened
by touches of orange and enhanced by
shimmering zellige mosaics.

Magnificent Riad deep in the hotel Gardens
Welcome to this magnificent Riad deep in the hotel
Gardens, with its three floors showcasing the splendours
of Arabo-Andalusian architecture. An exceptional setting
in which to savour Moroccan specialities prepared with
true passion by Chef Rachid Agouray.
If Le Marocain has earned its place as an institution
in Marrakech for over thirty years, and this is no
coincidence; it’s a result of the exquisite synergy
between the venue and its culinary offerings.
As soon as you arrive, you will be transported into the
splendours of a magnificent palace, where alcoves
welcome you like tiny jewel cases lined with soft
cushions.
Your dining experience will be a true voyage of
initiation, beginning with the ritual of ftour - a harira
soup served with dates, chbakias, honey and sesame
pastries - a combination as surprising as it is delicious.

From breakfast onwards, in this superb venue built
as a tribute to the Menara pavilion in Marrakech, the
restaurant, its terrace and buffets offer a cornucopia of
mouth-watering temptations.
Starting the day here is nothing short of idyllic. In the earlymorning calm, soothed by birdsong and the murmur of

An exclusive immersion into the art of Moroccan living
A symbol of Moroccan culture and craftsmanship, a Riad is a
traditional house built around a garden (the meaning of the
word in Arabic) or a patio, complete with a refreshing fountain
at its centre. It is a place of absolute tranquillity, removed from
the pressures of time, and the hustle and bustle of city life.
At La Mamounia, we wanted to offer our guests this experience
so they could enjoy an exceptional stay that combines
accommodation in the finest Marrakech architectural tradition
with the personalised services of our palace Hotel.
Three Riads have been built in our Gardens, each with its own
private entrance for absolute tranquillity and seclusion.
Savour the very essence of discreet luxury
Elegant and harmonious, the décor of the La Mamounia’s Riads
is on a par with that of our most opulent suites, mirroring the
vision of luxury that is synonymous with our historic hotel: a
subtle combination of exquisite materials, traditional Moroccan
craftsmanship and refined contemporary touches.
